# Edge-Case Taxonomy

A working enumeration of edge cases the agent should mentally walk through when targeting a function, handler, store call, hook, or component. Sections referenced from the main agent file as `§N`.

> **How to use:** When the diagnose phase picks a target, walk this taxonomy top-to-bottom for that target. Stop at the first edge case that produces a failing reproducer. That is the session.

---

## §1 — INPUT-VALUE EDGES

The classic "weird input" matrix. For any function/handler that accepts one of these types, ask: what does it do on each edge? Which are tested?

### Strings

- `""` (empty)
- `" "` (whitespace only)
- `"  leading"` / `"trailing  "` / `"  both  "`
- Very long: 1MB single-line, 10MB multi-line
- Unicode: `"日本語"`, emoji `"👨‍👩‍👧‍👦"` (ZWJ-grapheme), combining marks `"é"` vs `"é"` (NFC/NFD)
- RTL: `"שלום"`, mixed-direction `"hello שלום world"`
- Control characters: `"\0"`, `"\n"`, `"\r\n"`, `"\t"`, `"\x07"`
- BOM: `"\uFEFFhello"`
- Invalid UTF-8 bytes (Go: `string([]byte{0xff, 0xfe})`)
- Strings that look like other types: `"null"`, `"undefined"`, `"true"`, `"0"`, `"NaN"`, `"-0"`, `"1e308"`
- HTML/SQL/shell injection shapes: `"<script>"`, `"' OR 1=1 --"`, `"$(rm -rf /)"`
- Path-traversal: `"../../etc/passwd"`, `"..\\..\\..\\windows\\system32"`

### Numbers

- `0`, `-0`, `1`, `-1`
- `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER` / `math.MaxInt64`, plus 1
- `Number.MIN_SAFE_INTEGER` / `math.MinInt64`, minus 1
- `Number.EPSILON`, very small positives, denormals
- `Infinity`, `-Infinity`, `NaN`
- Negative where positive expected
- Floats where ints expected (or vice versa)
- Currency: rounding past 2 decimals, `0.1 + 0.2`

### Collections (slices, arrays, maps, lists)

- `nil` (Go) / `null` / `undefined` (TS)
- `[]` (empty)
- `[oneItem]`
- exactly `pageSize` items, `pageSize + 1`, `pageSize - 1`
- duplicates: `[a, a, a]`
- mixed types (TS: `[1, "two", null]`)
- very large: `len == 100_000`
- nested deeply: `[[[[[]]]]]`
- circular references (TS, JSON.stringify)
- map/object: missing key vs key-with-undefined vs key-with-null

### Booleans / nullables

- `true`, `false`
- `null`, `undefined`, missing field
- `0`, `""`, `[]` as falsy values when a real boolean was expected

### Dates / times

- `1970-01-01T00:00:00Z` (epoch)
- `1969-12-31T23:59:59Z` (pre-epoch)
- `2038-01-19T03:14:07Z` (32-bit overflow)
- Leap day: `2024-02-29`
- Leap second adjacent: `2016-12-31T23:59:60Z`
- DST transitions: `America/New_York` 2am→3am spring, 2am→1am fall
- UTC midnight vs local midnight
- Far future: `9999-12-31`
- Far past: `0001-01-01`
- Monotonic vs wall clock (Go `time.Time` carries both — comparisons can surprise)
- Time-zone offset of `+14:00` (Kiribati) and `-12:00` (Baker Island)

### IDs / UUIDs

- `""`, `"0"`, `"00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"`
- Lowercase vs uppercase UUID
- UUID with dashes vs without
- Database `id = 0` vs `id = -1` vs auto-increment overflow

